    <segment id="1" parent="11" relname="span">
Consistency is important in many ways and contributes to ease of use, transparency and many other concepts.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="10" relname="span"> An example of a problem with consistency is a program I used to work with on an AS/400.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="3" relname="concession"> Much of the time F3 was used to exit or go back from various sections of the program.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="8" relname="span"> Unfortunately, sometimes F7 was used to exit.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="9" relname="span"> The user had to get used to where each one applied.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="6" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> This interface was not consistent.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="12" relname="span"> This made it hard to use and reduced efficiency as well as making it quite un-friendly to the user.</segment>
